{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Van Dusen v. Barrack |ArgueDateA=January 8 |ArgueDateB=9 |ArgueYear=1964 |DecideDate=March 30 |DecideYear=1964 |FullName=Van Dusen, U.S. District Judge, et al. v. Barrack, Administratrix, et al. |USVol=376 |USPage=612 |ParallelCitations=84 S. Ct. 805; 11 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 945; 1964 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1537 |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding= |SCOTUS=1962-1965 |Majority=Goldberg |JoinMajority=Warren, Douglas, Clark, Harlan, Brennan, Stewart, White |Concurrence=Black |LawsApplied= }}
'''''Van Dusen v. Barrack''''', 376 U.S. 612 (1964), was a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case in which the Court held that when a case is transferred from a [[United States federal courts|federal court]] in one state to a federal court in another, the [[choice of law]] should be that of the state in which the case was originally filed.<ref>Yeazell, S.C. ''Civil Procedure, Seventh Edition.'' Aspen Publishers, New York, NY: 2008, p. 231</ref>
